observations.recommendation:
We recommended the Municipal Mayor direct the BAC to:
Ensure that the PPMPs of each end-user are meticulously and judiciously prepared since these will be consolidated to APP;
Prepare the APP following the step-by-step guide found on the GPPB website under downloadable forms, which is in accordance with the pertinent provisions of RA No. 9184 and GPPB Circular No. 07-2015.
Schedule each procurement activity with specificity, indicating the month, day, and year;
Adopt competitive bidding (public bidding) as the general mode of procurement and only resort to alternative modes if all the conditions set forth under Annex H of the revised IRR of RA 9184 are met; and
Capacitate and keep themselves abreast of updates on procurement law and the preparation of APP and apply them in the discharge of their functions.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Engineer to:
Develop and implement a system for the regular updating of project signboards, aligned with the schedule outlined in Section 3 of COA Circular No. 2013-004, to ensure that these accurately reflect the actual progress of infrastructure projects, thereby promoting transparency and reinforcing public accountability;
Implement standardized field inspection checklists and reporting templates to ensure that project signboards comply with the specifications in the DUPA;
Develop and adopt a uniform costing template or guidelines for the preparation of project signboard estimates, in order to promote consistency and fairness, and to minimize discretion in cost estimation; and
Evaluate and compare the costing of signboards included in the CSHP with those estimated separately, to determine appropriate and standardized costing practices.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
MSWDO to implement a streamlined processing workflow that aligns with the processing time stated in the Municipality’s Citizen’s Charter to ensure that requests for assistance particularly those of urgent nature, such as medical, burial, and food subsistence assistance are processed and released within the prescribed time frame;
MSWDO and Municipal Treasurer to consider requesting authority from the Sangguniang Bayan to establish a dedicated cash advance in accordance with COA Circular No. 97-002 exclusively for AICS program based on the average amount of the previous year’s weekly transaction to ensure sufficient funds are readily available to support urgent requests;
Municipal Treasurer’s Office to ensure timely liquidation of existing cash advances to avoid delays in the release of succeeding cash advance and install internal monitoring systems to track pending liquidations; and
MSWDO to immediately discontinue the practice of requiring barangay or mayoral endorsements unless explicitly mandated in DSWD guidelines and to strictly adhere to the schedule and parameters of FA set forth in Municipal Ordinance No. 2022-07 which includes observing the amount limits, frequency of availment, and eligibility criteria.
Furthermore, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor, through the MSWDO, conduct a comprehensive review of Ordinance No. 2022-07 and if deemed necessary, propose amendments to the Sangguniang Bayan to ensure that the FA amounts are updated and responsive to current needs and to include a clear, specific list of required documents per type of assistance, ensuring uniform implementation across all cases.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the PRAISE Committee and the Municipal Administrator to:
Submit written justification on the computation and 	granting of the across-the-board payment of the 2022 	PRAISE incentive, which included the newly hired 	employees;
Establish internal rules for the suitable criteria or appropriate guidelines in the selection of deserving 	employees who actually made exemplary suggestions, innovations or accomplishments that contributed to the efficiency, economy or improvement of government operations, as evidenced by the awards received by the municipal government;
Submit subsequent amendments made in the PRAISE 	guidelines to the Civil Service Commission for their evaluation and approval; and
Immediately submit the Annual PRAISE report for CY 	2022 to the same, with a copy furnished to this office, and submit future reports on or before the 30th day of January of the following year.
We likewise recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to stop the practice of charging prior-year expenses against the current year’s appropriation to avoid future infractions. If the incurrence of expenses at year-end cannot be dispensed with, unpaid obligations shall be recorded as payables and shall be supported with complete documentation.

We have recommended that the Management:

require their suppliers to submit all the documents required by law and meticulously examine their legal, technical and financial capacity;


refrain from entering into contracts with suppliers whose line of business/industry is not within the scope of the subject transaction;



ensure that the contracts/purchase orders contain the required warranty clause; 


To accept only duly executed Omnibus Sworn Statements containing all the required declarations; and

comply with the online posting requirement for transparency and accountability.

We have recommended the following:

The Inventory Committee to:
conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the Municipality and;

render a Report on the Physical count of the Road Networks System. 


The Municipal General Service Officer to: 
render a Report on Local Road Network and Road Map;
keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components and;

The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Service Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.

The Municipal Accountant to:
prepare the JEV to record the beginning balance of the local road network and its components;

prepare and maintain a Local Road Network Ledger Card; and

keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network.

Given the foregoing facts, we have recommended the management agreed to:

strictly adhere to the accounting and reporting guidelines on property management as provided in the MNGAS;

require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of all the properties owned by the municipality;

ensure that the GSO reconcile its records with the Accounting Office and adjust accordingly to reflect the proper valuation of PPEs in the financial statements; and

1.7       We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:
a. 	the Municipal Accountant to adjust the Cash in Bank, LCCA and other affected accounts pertaining to the misstatements;
b. the Municipal Accountant to conduct corrective control on monitoring of outstanding checks and prepare monthly bank reconciliation prior the closing of books by requesting snapshots from the bank in order to adjust the book reconciling items such as the unrecorded receipts pertaining to unrecognized deposits, and interest income to ensure accuracy of the Cash-in-Bank, LCCA account in the financial statement.  Also, adjust the book errors but ensure that the same are duly supported with documents;
c. 	the Municipal Treasurer to timely submit all documents to the Municipal Accountant in order to avoid delay in recording all transactions and to cancel the unclaimed stale checks and furnish the Accountant with the duplicate copies of DV and its supporting documents, for the preparation of the JEV following the procedures prescribed to ensure recording of cancellation; and
d. 	the Municipal Treasurer to call the attention or inform the payees of those cancelled checks to surrender the stale checks to her so she could issue new checks.

We recommended that Management substantially comply with the Circular by directing:
The concerned/responsible offices, first and foremost, to properly and adequately plan the retrieval of records, conduct of inventory and recording of LRNs;
The Inventory Committee to properly conduct physical inventory of LRNs by segregating and recognizing the cost of each component of the local roads, if possible;
The Municipal Engineer to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer-Designate on the retrieval of the documents related to LRNs constructed prior to CY2009; and
The Property Officer-Designate and the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the pertinent records and reports.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Engineer to:
submit proofs of the suspension of works and ascertain if the duration of suspension is reasonable and in accordance with the provision of RA 9184;
require all inspectors to prepare a monitoring/inspection/accomplishment report for every site inspection which must be duly documented with photos;
recommend suspension of works only when supported with proofs to back-up reasons for such; and
prepare Contract Time Extensions and Suspensions of Works Orders in accordance with RA No. 9184

We have recommended the Management to: 

direct the Municipal Accountant to restate the CY 2020 Financial Statements of the Municipality to recognize the unrecorded Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) and Personnel Services accounts and their corresponding Payable Accounts;

instruct the Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with each other for the timely transmittal of the Obligation Request and Status Forms and to reconcile their records at least every quarter to determine and address discrepancies;

issue closing instructions particularly on observing cut-off date and submission of documents needed as basis in recognizing payables and commitments; 

identify the bottlenecks in processing their transactions for disbursements and design an improved flowchart to fast track their procedures; and

Strictly adhere with accounting policies and standards set by the Commission such that all lawful expenditures and obligations incurred during the year shall be taken-up in the accounts of that year

Given the foregoing facts, we have recommended the management agreed to:

Strictly adhere to the accounting and reporting guidelines on property management as provided in the MNGAS;

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of all the properties owned by the municipality;

Ensure that the GSO reconcile its records with the Accounting Office and adjust accordingly to reflect the proper valuation of PPEs in the financial statements; and

Provide yearly depreciation for all depreciable properties in accordance with the above-mentioned rules and regulation.

